{"action_ids":["911","891"],"summary":"Amending soils with manures and agricultural composts can have several effects on soil health. The application of manure or compost has been found to increase microbial biomass, while poultry manure specifically has been shown to increase microbial respiration (911). In terms of soil structure and erosion, one study found that high rates of cotton gin compost and poultry manure improved soil structure and reduced soil loss (891). Another study noted lower soil loss and runoff when manure was used with other treatments (911), and a separate study linked manure and compost application to higher organic matter, larger soil aggregations, and improved physical properties (911).

When it comes to nutrient management, three studies reported reduced nutrient loss and higher nitrogen levels with farmyard or poultry manure application (911). Conversely, one study found that high application rates of cotton gin compost and poultry manure increased nutrient loss (891), and another observed higher nitrate leaching (911). The timing of application can also be a factor, with one study finding that applying farmyard manure in winter instead of autumn led to lower nutrient loss (911).

Soil organic carbon and matter can also be affected. Four studies found higher carbon levels after manure application (911). While one study reported increased organic matter from manure and compost (911), two other studies found no change in organic matter levels from manure application (911). Finally, four studies have shown that applying manures or composts can lead to higher crop yields (911).","query":"What are the wider soil health effects of amending soils with animal-derived products like manure or composts?"}

